                <head>97. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On June 19, 1961, Admiral Burke, Chief of Naval Operations, forwarded to
                    Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> a memorandum of
                    the same date to the Joint Chiefs of Staff in which he argued that Chairman
                        <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> may have “deliberately
                    raised the alarm on Berlin in order to seek concessions elsewhere. One of the
                    most dangerous areas for seeking such a concession would be Southeast Asia. He
                    may envision a relaxation of the Berlin crisis in exchange for an understanding
                    that the U.S. would not forcefully resist further Communist expansion in
                    Southeast Asia.” For text of Burkeʼs memorandum, see <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v14#pg_129">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1961–1963, volume XIV, pages
                        129</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v14#pg_130">130</ref>.</p>
            </div>
